# nginx reverse proxy config
server {
  listen 80;
  server_name app.example.com;
  location / {
    proxy_pass http://localhost:3000;
    proxy_set_header Host $host;
    proxy_set_header X-Real-IP $remote_addr;
  }
}

# Load balancing
upstream backend {
  server 10.0.0.1:3000 weight=3;
  server 10.0.0.2:3000 weight=2;
  server 10.0.0.3:3000 backup;
}
server {
  listen 80;
  location / {
    proxy_pass http://backend;
  }
}

commands.details:
Basic NGINX reverse proxy config:
server {
  listen 80;
  location / { proxy_pass http://localhost:3000; }
}

Load balancing upstream block:
upstream backend {
  server 10.0.0.1:3000 weight=3;
  server 10.0.0.2:3000 weight=2;
}

A reverse proxy sits between clients and your backend servers. The most common use case is running multiple services on a single server. You might have a Node.js API on port 3000, a Python app on port 5000, and a static website served by NGINX on port 80. The reverse proxy routes requests to the correct backend based on domain name or URL path.

SSL termination is another major benefit. The reverse proxy handles TLS encryption/decryption, allowing backend applications to communicate over plain HTTP internally. This simplifies certificate management and reduces CPU load on application servers.

Health checks automatically detect failed servers and stop sending them traffic until they recover.
